The eigenvectors of $L$ form an orthonormal basis of $\mathbb{R}^n$. The first eigenvector $v_1$ is the constant vector and its corresponding eigenvalue is $0$. The remaining eigenvectors $v_2, v_3, \dots, v_n$ correspond to strictly positive eigenvalues. The second smallest eigenvalue $\lambda_2$ is called the algebraic connectivity of $G$.

The algebraic connectivity of $G$ is an important measure of the connectivity of $G$. A higher algebraic connectivity implies a stronger connectivity of the graph. It is also related to the number of cuts needed to disconnect the graph. Specifically, the number of cuts needed to disconnect $G$ is at least $\lambda_2^{-1}$.

Furthermore, the algebraic connectivity of $G$ is related to the spectral gap of $G$. The spectral gap of $G$ is the difference between the first and second smallest eigenvalues of $L$. A larger spectral gap implies a stronger connectivity of the graph. Specifically, the spectral gap of $G$ is at most $2\lambda_2$.

The algebraic connectivity of $G$ can be computed efficiently using the power iteration method. The power iteration method is an iterative algorithm that computes the dominant eigenvector of a matrix. Starting with an initial vector, the power iteration method repeatedly applies the matrix and normalizes the result. The algorithm converges to the dominant eigenvector of the matrix, which corresponds to the eigenvalue with the largest absolute value.

In summary, the algebraic connectivity of a graph is a fundamental measure of its connectivity and can be efficiently computed using the power iteration method. It is related to the number of cuts needed to disconnect the graph and the spectral gap of the Laplacian matrix.

